<subSubSection id="8C8E6575FFC36A7CFF4D9AAB144DBA6D" pageId="56" pageNumber="814" type="reference_group">
<paragraph id="C42B36FEFFC36A7CFF4D9AAB1F42B609" blockId="56.[176,1382,3314,3473]" pageId="56" pageNumber="814">
<emphasis id="F6E0EAECFFC36A7CFF4D9AAB1F4CB621" bold="true" box="[177,332,3314,3347]" pageId="56" pageNumber="814">Taxonomy.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="03944D7DFFC36A7CFEA09AAB1D3AB621" authority="Temminck, 1840" authorityName="Temminck" authorityYear="1840" box="[348,826,3314,3347]" class="Mammalia" family="Vespertilionidae" genus="Vespertilio" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="56" pageNumber="814" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="macrotis">Vespertilio macrotis Temminck, 1840</taxonomicName>
, 
<materialsCitation id="74FC3CA3FFC36A7CFCB69AAB1F42B609" ID-GBIF-Occurrence="3783319305" pageId="56" pageNumber="814">
“le district de Padang, ile 
<collectingRegion id="0650F81CFFC36A7CFB4C9AAB1B50B621" box="[1200,1360,3314,3347]" country="Indonesia" name="Sumatera Selatan" pageId="56" pageNumber="814">de Sumatra</collectingRegion>
,” 
<collectingCountry id="BC83766EFFC36A7CFF4E9B431F3EB609" box="[178,318,3354,3387]" name="Indonesia" pageId="56" pageNumber="814">Indonesia</collectingCountry>
.
</materialsCitation>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="C42B36FEFFC36A7CFF4E9B18144DBA6D" blockId="56.[176,1382,3314,3473]" lastBlockId="56.[2066,2659,278,705]" pageId="56" pageNumber="814">
<taxonomicName id="03944D7DFFC36A7CFF4E9B181F92B650" baseAuthorityName="Temminck" baseAuthorityYear="1840" box="[178,402,3393,3426]" class="Mammalia" family="Vespertilionidae" genus="Hypsugo" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="56" pageNumber="814" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="macrotis">Hypsugo macrotis</taxonomicName>
has been considered conspecific with 
<taxonomicName id="03944D7DFFC36A7CFC4A9B181A66B650" baseAuthorityName="Horsfield" baseAuthorityYear="1824" box="[950,1126,3393,3426]" class="Mammalia" family="Vespertilionidae" genus="Pipistrellus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="56" pageNumber="814" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="imbricatus">H. imbricatus</taxonomicName>
, but they are generally recognized as distinct species based on morphological data. It appears to be closely related to 
<taxonomicName id="03944D7DFFC36A7CF6F2974F17DFBA05" authorityName="Jentink" authorityYear="1890" box="[2318,2527,278,311]" class="Mammalia" family="Vespertilionidae" genus="Hypsugo" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="56" pageNumber="814" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="vordermanni">H. vordermanni</taxonomicName>
, which is morphologically very similar. Monotypic.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="8C8E6575FFC36A7CF7EE9734178BBAE7" pageId="56" pageNumber="814" type="distribution">
<caption id="90EB6676FFC36A7CF7EE9734178BBAE7" ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6397998" ID-Zenodo-Dep="6397998" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6397998/files/figure.png" inLine="true" pageId="56" pageNumber="814" targetBox="[1451,2043,289,703]" targetPageId="56">
<paragraph id="C42B36FEFFC36A7CF7EE9734178BBAE7" blockId="56.[2066,2659,278,705]" pageId="56" pageNumber="814">
<emphasis id="F6E0EAECFFC36A7CF7EE973416C2BAB4" bold="true" box="[2066,2242,365,390]" pageId="56" pageNumber="814">Distribution.</emphasis>
W Peninsular 
<collectingCountry id="BC83766EFFC36A7CF65E97341419BAB4" box="[2466,2585,365,390]" name="Malaysia" pageId="56" pageNumber="814">Malaysia</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry id="BC83766EFFC36A7CF5D297341676BA9F" name="Singapore" pageId="56" pageNumber="814">Singapore</collectingCountry>
, NE Sumatra, and Padang, Enggano, Bali, and Lombok Is.
</paragraph>
</caption>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="8C8E6575FFC36A7CF7EE978219EFB8B4" pageId="56" pageNumber="814" type="description">
<paragraph id="C42B36FEFFC36A7CF7EE978219EFB8B4" blockId="56.[2066,2659,278,705]" lastBlockId="56.[1452,2659,711,1494]" pageId="56" pageNumber="814">
<emphasis id="F6E0EAECFFC36A7CF7EE97821712BACE" bold="true" box="[2066,2322,475,508]" pageId="56" pageNumber="814">Descriptive notes.</emphasis>
Head-body ¢. 
<quantity id="036C9B1BFFC36A7CF6109782145BBACE" box="[2540,2651,475,508]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.0" pageId="56" pageNumber="814" unit="mm" value="50.0">50 mm</quantity>
, tal ¢.20 mim, ear c¢.13-5 mm, forearm 31-7-34-5 mm; weight 4-6 g. Dorsal pelage of the Big-eared Pipistrelle is reddish brown (hairs with dark brown bases); ventral pelage is a little paler. Ears are comparatively long, broad, and subtriangular with broadly rounded tip; tragus is short, broad, and hatchet-shaped. Wing membranes are translucent white with brown tinge. Skull is larger and shorter than in Vordermann’s Pipistrelle (
<taxonomicName id="03944D7DFFC36A7CF6D0954F1453B805" authorityName="Jentink" authorityYear="1890" box="[2348,2643,790,823]" class="Mammalia" family="Vespertilionidae" genus="Hypsugo" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="56" pageNumber="814" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="vordermanni">Hypsugo vordermanni</taxonomicName>
); rostrum is short; forehead has evenly sloping profile. P* is minute and completely displaced inwardly; C' and P* are in contact.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="8C8E6575FFC36A7CFA5295D51733B8E7" pageId="56" pageNumber="814" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph id="C42B36FEFFC36A7CFA5295D51733B8E7" blockId="56.[1452,2659,711,1494]" pageId="56" pageNumber="814">
<emphasis id="F6E0EAECFFC36A7CFA5295D5181DB89F" bold="true" box="[1454,1565,908,941]" pageId="56" pageNumber="814">Habitat.</emphasis>
The Big-eared Pipistrelle has been reported foraging over open mudflats in coastal regions in Peninsular 
<collectingCountry id="BC83766EFFC36A7CF8B795ED19C1B8E7" box="[1867,1985,948,981]" name="Malaysia" pageId="56" pageNumber="814">Malaysia</collectingCountry>
and in lowland rainforest.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="8C8E6575FFC36A7CFA519582196EBF16" pageId="56" pageNumber="814" type="food_feeding">
<paragraph id="C42B36FEFFC36A7CFA519582196EBF16" blockId="56.[1452,2659,711,1494]" pageId="56" pageNumber="814">
<emphasis id="F6E0EAECFFC36A7CFA51958218B5B8CE" bold="true" box="[1453,1717,987,1020]" pageId="56" pageNumber="814">Food and Feeding.</emphasis>
The Big-eared Pipistrelle has been observed foraging 
<quantity id="036C9B1BFFC36A7CF640958217EFB8CE" box="[2492,2543,987,1020]" metricMagnitude="0" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.0" pageId="56" pageNumber="814" unit="m" value="3.0">3 m</quantity>
around the edge and canopy ofa forest.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="8C8E6575FFC36A7CFA52927318ECBF41" pageId="56" pageNumber="814" type="breeding">
<paragraph id="C42B36FEFFC36A7CFA52927318ECBF41" blockId="56.[1452,2659,711,1494]" pageId="56" pageNumber="814">
<emphasis id="F6E0EAECFFC36A7CFA5292731834BF79" bold="true" box="[1454,1588,1066,1099]" pageId="56" pageNumber="814">Breeding.</emphasis>
Big-eared Pipistrelles form maternity colonies during the breeding season with 10-20 individuals.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="8C8E6575FFC36A7CFA5092201997BFDB" pageId="56" pageNumber="814" type="activity">
<paragraph id="C42B36FEFFC36A7CFA5092201997BFDB" blockId="56.[1452,2659,711,1494]" pageId="56" pageNumber="814">
<emphasis id="F6E0EAECFFC36A7CFA5092201895BFA8" bold="true" box="[1452,1685,1145,1178]" pageId="56" pageNumber="814">Activity patterns.</emphasis>
A maternity colony in 
<collectingCountry id="BC83766EFFC36A7CF82E92201648BFA8" box="[2002,2120,1145,1178]" name="Malaysia" pageId="56" pageNumber="814">Malaysia</collectingCountry>
was recorded roosting between a pipeline and a pillar and Big-eared Pipistrelles were observed switching roosts in response to a feral cat disturbing their roost.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="8C8E6575FFC36A7CFA5192B61460BE22" box="[1453,2656,1263,1296]" pageId="56" pageNumber="814" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph id="C42B36FEFFC36A7CFA5192B61460BE22" blockId="56.[1452,2659,711,1494]" box="[1453,2656,1263,1296]" pageId="56" pageNumber="814">
<emphasis id="F6E0EAECFFC36A7CFA5192B6164FBE22" bold="true" box="[1453,2127,1263,1296]" pageId="56" pageNumber="814">Movements, Home range and Social organization.</emphasis>
Big-eared Pipistrelles roost in colonies.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="8C8E6575FFC36A7CFA52934E1648BEB5" pageId="56" pageNumber="814" type="conservation">
<paragraph id="C42B36FEFFC36A7CFA52934E1648BEB5" blockId="56.[1452,2659,711,1494]" pageId="56" pageNumber="814">
<emphasis id="F6E0EAECFFC36A7CFA52934E190FBE0A" bold="true" box="[1454,1807,1303,1336]" pageId="56" pageNumber="814">Status and Conservation.</emphasis>
Classified as Data Deficient on The IUCN Red List. The Bigeared Pipistrelle is considered a rare species throughout its scattered distribution, but it may be more common than currently known.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="8C8E6575FFC36A7CFA5293CC188EBEE4" pageId="56" pageNumber="814" type="bibRefCitation_list">
